financial analysis. Drawing on two years of fieldwork in a Swiss bank, Stefan Leins argues that financial analysts construct stories of possible economic futures, presenting them as coherent and grounded in expert research and analysis. In so doing, they establish a role for themselves-not necessarily by laying bare empirically verifiable trends but rather by presenting the market as something that makes sense and is worth investing in. Stories of Capitalism is a nuanced look at how banks continue to boost investment-even in unstable markets-and a rare insider's look into the often opaque financial practices that shape the global economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBanks and banking -- Switzerland. 0aBanks and bankingzSwitzerland. 0aFinance -- Social aspects. 0aFinancexSocial aspects. 0aFinancial analysts. 0aFinancial services industry -- Employees. 0aFinancial services industryxEmployees. 0aInvestment banking -- Social aspects -- Switzerland. 0aInvestment bankingxSocial aspectszSwitzerland. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aSwiss banking.  aanthropology of finance.  aeconomic anthropology.  aethnography.  afinancial analysis.  aforecasting.  anarratives.  aneoliberalism.  aprediction.  avaluation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106885800 cprintz978022652339240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226523569zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226523569/original  a978-3-11-068858-0 University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-all